{
  "doc_id": "8709",
  "text": "Inhibition of KCNJ5 WT has the potential to cause cardiac side effects due to KCNJ5 expression in the atrium, where it contributes to slowing of the heart rate in response to acetylcholine [CITATION_1] . However, loss of K + selectivity in KCNJ5 G151R and KCNJ5 L168R channels as well as loss of sensitivity to the K + channel blockers barium (7) and tertiapin-Q [CITATION_2] suggest that the pore of mutant channels is sufficiently altered to enable small molecules to block ion passage through the mutant, but not the WT, channel.",
